Appendix 16
For Hallinskidi see Reuter, p. 237; Simrock, Handbuch, p. 277; Gering (Edda trans., p. 320): &ldquo;gebogene Schneeschuhe habend.&rdquo; Much (in Festschrift Heinzel, p. 259), connecting -skidi with Celtic skêto, skêda (English: humerus, scapula) and taking halle for &ldquo;stone,&rdquo; ventures to propose the reconstruction &ldquo;he with the stone shoulder . . . which would presuppose a similar story as that about Pelops and his ivory shoulder.&rdquo;
As concerns mjötvidr, A.

Appendix 20
Such stories are no jokes, although they make this impression when they cross our way in Eurasian folklore. &ldquo;Air&rdquo; is a strictly astronomical and, therefore, also a &ldquo;religious&rdquo; term. Thus, we hear from Rabbi Eleazar b. Pedath (ca. A.D. 270): &ldquo;Als def Pharaoh aus Agypten auszog, die Israeliten zu verfolgen, erhoben sie ihre Augen gen Himmel und sahen den Engelsfürsten Ägyptens in der Luft fliegen.&rdquo;
&ldquo;That signifies the fall of Egypt,&rdquo; adds Bertholet, who mentions this case in his article on the &ldquo;guardian angel of Persia&rdquo; (Festschrift Pavry, p.

Appendix 27
See A. Oppenheim, “Mesopotamian Mythology,&quot; Or. 17 (1948), p. 40: &ldquo;After Enkidu tossed towards her . . . what is euphemistically termed the &lsquo;right thigh&rsquo; of the bull, the goddess and her devotees performed age-old rites over the part of the bull.&rdquo;
True as this statement certainly is, it does not explain much — nor is it even asked why it must be the right thigh (imittu; compare H.
